# @SHBMV03P161B_BEG_WABAB أبو بكر قال ثنا @TR1_ABAB@ عبد الأعلى بن عبد الأعلى عن محمد بن إسحاق قال رأيت القاسم بن محمد بمنى معتمرا متغمطا وكان لا يفيض حتى ينفر في آخر أيام التشريق. @SHBMV03P161B_END_WABAB
PageV03P161
# @COMMENT: This passage is not located in HSNX. This is an identity passage, here to establish that Ibn Isḥāq had met al-Qāsim b. Muḥammad. al-Qāsim b. Muḥammad b. Abī Bakr al-Ṣiddīq, was the grandson of the first caliph. His daughter, Farwah, was married to Muḥammad b. ʿAlī b. Ḥusayn, b. ʿAlī b. Abī Ṭālib. He was known as a critic of the Qadarīyah movement and a collector of traditions, which he arranged alphabetically. He died in 108, at the age of 70 or 72 (TKXXV05P142C to TKXXV05P148F). Ibn Isḥāq is quoted in unwitnesses passages speaking about the qualities of al-Qāsim b. Muḥammad, giving the impression that he knew him fairly well (JWSSV01P351I, as well as JWZXV07P123C), similar fragments are also found in WYBWS, WAZID, and WSACD. @EC_02/23/23@ He is mentioned as a link in six different chains of transmission in HSNX, but in none of these is he mentioned as a direct source. Ibn Isḥāq does transmit directly from his son, ʿAbd al-Raḥmān b. al-Qāsim b. Muḥammad, in WZATB on HSNXV02P381B (also see WSHAK). al-Qāsim b. Muḥammad is also mentioned in WSACD in several places. In addition, he is cited in traditions related via WISUL, WMHAL, WYBWS, and WSFAB. WMSAH includes a story in which al-Qāsim b. Muḥammad is a character as well as traditions in which he is a transmitter. @EC_02/23/23@

